    "shortDesc": "Corneal Tattoo\nCorneal tattooing is a specialized ophthalmic procedure where pigment is embedded into the\ncornea—the transparent front surface of the eye—to improve cosmetic appearance or correct\nvisual disturbances. Though it is relatively rare, this procedure can be both medica",
    "seoTitle": "Corneal Tattoo - Causes, Symptoms, Diagnosis & Treatment | Ashu Laser Vision Mumbai",
    "seoDescription": "Learn about Corneal Tattoo: causes, symptoms, diagnosis, treatment, prevention & FAQs. Expert eye care by Dr. Shahnawaz Kazi at Ashu Laser Vision, Andheri Mumbai - Super Specialty Eye Hospital since 2004. Book consultation.",
    "keywords": "Corneal Tattoo, Corneal Tattoo treatment Mumbai, Corneal Tattoo causes symptoms, Corneal Tattoo diagnosis, eye diseases Andheri, Ashu Laser Vision, best eye hospital Mumbai",
    "contentMd": "# Corneal Tattoo\n\nSource: `Eye Diseases & Conditions-compressed.pdf`, pages 707-711.\n\n_No embedded image was found for this section in the PDF._\n\n## Extracted text\n\n<!-- Page 707 -->\nCorneal Tattoo\nCorneal tattooing is a specialized ophthalmic procedure where pigment is embedded into the\ncornea—the transparent front surface of the eye—to improve cosmetic appearance or correct\nvisual disturbances. Though it is relatively rare, this procedure can be both medically necessary\nand aesthetically beneficial for patients with corneal opacities, trauma, or congenital defects.\nHistorically performed for centuries, corneal tattooing has evolved into a safer and more\neffective method, aided by advancements in medical-grade dyes and microsurgical techniques.\nSymptoms and Causes\n\n<!-- Page 708 -->\nWhy is Corneal Tattooing Needed?\nCorneal tattoos are typically performed for either cosmetic or therapeutic reasons.\nCommon Reasons Include:\nDisfiguring corneal scars due to trauma, infection, or surgery\nLeukomas (white opacities) following corneal disease\nIrregular pupil shape or size (e.g., traumatic mydriasis)\nPhotophobia (light sensitivity) due to iris defects\nCongenital eye abnormalities\nBlind eyes with an unsightly appearance\nSymptoms that May Lead to Corneal Tattooing:\nWhite or grayish discoloration of the eye\nDisfigurement or asymmetry compared to the other eye\nCosmetic dissatisfaction\nSensitivity to light\nVisual distortion due to corneal irregularities\nDiagnosis and Tests\nBefore recommending corneal tattooing, an ophthalmologist performs a thorough eye\nexamination, including:\nSlit-lamp biomicroscopy: To assess corneal thickness, health, and any underlying\npathology\nVisual acuity testing: To determine if any vision remains in the affected eye\nCorneal topography or tomography: To map the shape of the cornea\nAssessment of ocular history: Previous injuries, infections, or surgeries must be\nevaluated\nPhotography and color matching: To customize the pigment to the patient’s natural eye\ncolor (if cosmetic purposes are intended)\nManagement and Treatment\nCorneal tattooing is performed by a trained ophthalmic surgeon and typically involves:\n\n<!-- Page 709 -->\nProcedure Overview:\nDone under local anesthesia (topical or injectable)\nPigment is introduced into or onto the corneal stroma (middle layer)\nMay be done using needles, lamellar pocket techniques, or superficial applications\nThe procedure can take 30 to 60 minutes depending on the complexity\nPost-Procedure Care:\nAntibiotic and anti-inflammatory eye drops\nEye shield for protection\nAvoid rubbing or touching the eye\nFollow-up exams to monitor healing and color retention\nCorneal Tattoo Types & Surgery\nTypes of Corneal Tattooing:\n1. Superficial Corneal Tattooing\no\nDye is applied to the outer layer (epithelium)\no\nBest for minor discoloration or when vision is already lost\no\nLess invasive, but may fade over time\n2. Intrastromal Corneal Tattooing\no\nDye is injected or embedded within the stroma\no\nOffers more durable and stable results\no\nPreferred for deeper or more significant defects\n3. Lamellar Pocket Tattooing\no\nA thin pocket is created inside the cornea to place the dye\no\nProvides controlled pigment placement and reduces risk of surface irregularities\nSurgical Considerations:\nThe eye must be free from active infection or inflammation\nBlind or non-seeing eyes are more commonly selected for cosmetic tattooing\nCustomized pigments may be used to match the iris color or cover defects precisely\nPrevention\nCorneal tattooing is typically performed after an eye condition has occurred, so preventing the\nunderlying cause is key:\n\n<!-- Page 710 -->\nUse protective eyewear to prevent trauma\nTreat corneal infections promptly\nManage conditions like herpes simplex keratitis or corneal dystrophies\nAvoid exposure to harmful chemicals or radiation\nRegular eye check-ups and prompt treatment of any corneal abnormalities can prevent scarring\nand opacities that may require tattooing later.\nOutlook / Prognosis\nThe prognosis after corneal tattooing depends on the purpose of the procedure:\nCosmetic outcomes are generally positive, with improved eye appearance and reduced\nsocial or emotional distress\nTherapeutic outcomes may reduce light sensitivity or glare\nVision is usually not improved, especially if the tattoo is performed on a blind or severely\ndamaged eye\nResults may fade over time, and repeat procedures might be necessary\nLiving with a Corneal Tattoo\nMost individuals adapt well to life after a corneal tattoo. Post-procedure adjustments may\ninclude:\nRegular use of lubricating eye drops\nAwareness of possible fading or need for touch-ups\nAnnual eye exams to monitor eye health\nPsychological comfort from cosmetic improvement, especially in visible injuries\nFor those with vision in the tattooed eye, ongoing assessment is critical to ensure no adverse\neffects on sight.\nAdditional Common Questions\nIs corneal tattooing painful?\nNo. The procedure is performed under local anesthesia, and most patients experience only mild\ndiscomfort afterward.\n\n<!-- Page 711 -->\nHow long does the tattoo last?\nIntrastromal tattoos can last several years or longer. Superficial tattoos may fade faster and\nrequire reapplication.\nCan the tattoo be removed?\nNot easily. Corneal tattoo removal is complex and may require surgical intervention such as\ncorneal transplantation.\nIs it safe?\nWhen performed by a skilled ophthalmic surgeon, corneal tattooing is generally safe. Risks\ninclude infection, inflammation, or pigment dispersion.\nFAQs\nQ: Can I get a corneal tattoo for aesthetic purposes only?\nA: Yes, some individuals choose corneal tattooing to correct asymmetry or disfigurement,\nespecially in a blind eye.\nQ: Is it covered by insurance?\nA: If medically necessary (e.g., to reduce light sensitivity), it might be covered. Cosmetic cases\noften are not.\nQ: Can both eyes be tattooed?\nA: It's rare and typically unnecessary. Usually, only one eye is affected by trauma or scarring.\nQ: What colors are available?\nA: Pigments can be custom-mixed to match natural eye color or achieve specific cosmetic\nresults, such as black, blue-gray, green, or brown shades.\n"
