    "shortDesc": "Gonioscopy\nGonioscopy is a specialized eye examination technique used to visualize the anterior chamber\nangle—the area where the cornea and iris meet. This angle is critical for the drainage of aqueous\nhumor (the fluid in the eye). If the angle is too narrow or blocked, it can le",
    "seoTitle": "Gonioscopy - Causes, Symptoms, Diagnosis & Treatment | Ashu Laser Vision Mumbai",
    "seoDescription": "Learn about Gonioscopy: causes, symptoms, diagnosis, treatment, prevention & FAQs. Expert eye care by Dr. Shahnawaz Kazi at Ashu Laser Vision, Andheri Mumbai - Super Specialty Eye Hospital since 2004. Book consultation.",
    "keywords": "Gonioscopy, Gonioscopy treatment Mumbai, Gonioscopy causes symptoms, Gonioscopy diagnosis, eye diseases Andheri, Ashu Laser Vision, best eye hospital Mumbai",
    "contentMd": "# Gonioscopy\n\nSource: `Eye Diseases & Conditions-compressed.pdf`, pages 712-716.\n\n_No embedded image was found for this section in the PDF._\n\n## Extracted text\n\n<!-- Page 712 -->\nGonioscopy\nGonioscopy is a specialized eye examination technique used to visualize the anterior chamber\nangle—the area where the cornea and iris meet. This angle is critical for the drainage of aqueous\nhumor (the fluid in the eye). If the angle is too narrow or blocked, it can lead to glaucoma, a\nserious eye condition that can result in vision loss.\nSince this area cannot be seen with the naked eye or a standard slit-lamp exam, gonioscopy\nprovides essential insights for diagnosing and managing various forms of glaucoma and other\nanterior segment disorders.\nSymptoms and Causes Leading to Gonioscopy\nWhy Is Gonioscopy Performed?\nGonioscopy is not performed as a routine exam for all patients. It’s recommended when a patient\nshows symptoms or has risk factors associated with angle-related eye conditions, especially\nglaucoma.\nCommon Symptoms That Prompt Gonioscopy:\nElevated intraocular pressure (IOP)\nVision changes or loss of peripheral vision\nEye pain, especially in low light conditions\nSeeing halos around lights\nRedness and discomfort in the eyes\nUnderlying Conditions That May Require Gonioscopy:\nPrimary open-angle glaucoma\nAngle-closure glaucoma (acute or chronic)\nNeovascular glaucoma\nTrauma-induced angle recession\nCongenital angle abnormalities\nTumors or foreign bodies in the anterior chamber\nDiagnosis and Tests\n\n<!-- Page 713 -->\nWhat Happens During Gonioscopy?\nGonioscopy is performed using a goniolens or gonioscope, a special lens placed gently on the\nsurface of the eye after applying a numbing drop. The lens allows the ophthalmologist to see the\ndrainage angle and assess its structure and openness.\nSteps in the Procedure:\n1. Topical anesthetic is applied to prevent discomfort\n2. A goniolens is placed directly on the cornea\n3. The doctor uses a slit-lamp or microscope to examine the angle\n4. The angle is graded based on visibility of angle structures (Schwalbe's line, trabecular\nmeshwork, scleral spur, and ciliary body)\nOther Diagnostic Tests Often Done Alongside Gonioscopy:\nTonometry (measuring IOP)\nVisual field testing\nOptical coherence tomography (OCT)\nPachymetry (measuring corneal thickness)\nManagement and Treatment\nInterpreting Gonioscopy Results\nOpen angles: Suggest lower risk for angle-closure glaucoma\nNarrow angles: Indicate a risk for acute angle-closure attacks\nClosed angles: Require immediate treatment to reduce intraocular pressure\nAbnormal structures or pigmentation: May suggest trauma, pigment dispersion\nsyndrome, or neovascularization\nTreatment Based on Findings:\nOpen-angle glaucoma: Managed with medications, laser trabeculoplasty, or surgery\nAngle-closure: Often requires laser peripheral iridotomy (LPI) to relieve pressure\nAbnormal angle anatomy: May require close monitoring or surgical correction\nGonioscopy is critical in determining the appropriate course of treatment for each individual.\nGonioscopy Types & Surgical Use\n\n<!-- Page 714 -->\nTypes of Gonioscopy\n1. Direct Gonioscopy\no\nPerformed with contact lenses (e.g., Koeppe lens) under an operating microscope\no\nCommon in surgical settings\n2. Indirect Gonioscopy\no\nDone using lenses like the Goldmann or Zeiss goniolens\no\nMost common in clinics for routine diagnostic use\nGonioscopy in Surgery\nGonioscopy is not a surgical procedure itself but is used during minimally invasive glaucoma\nsurgeries (MIGS). Surgeons use gonioscopic guidance to implant drainage devices or perform\nangle-based procedures such as:\nGoniosynechialysis\nTrabectome surgery\nGoniotomy or ab interno trabeculotomy\nPrevention\nGonioscopy is a diagnostic tool, not a preventive measure. However, early use of gonioscopy\ncan help prevent vision loss by detecting angle abnormalities before symptoms occur.\nPreventive Eye Care Tips:\nRegular comprehensive eye exams, especially after age 40\nAnnual screening for individuals with a family history of glaucoma\nImmediate evaluation after eye trauma\nRoutine IOP checks for high-risk individuals\nOutlook / Prognosis\nGonioscopy plays a pivotal role in early glaucoma diagnosis and management, often\ndetermining whether intervention is needed to prevent vision loss.\nEarly detection allows for effective treatment with eye drops, lasers, or surgery\nDelayed diagnosis of angle-closure or neovascular changes can lead to irreversible\ndamage\nRepeat gonioscopy may be required periodically to monitor disease progression\n\n<!-- Page 715 -->\nWhen integrated into regular ophthalmic care, gonioscopy significantly improves long-term\noutcomes for glaucoma patients.\nLiving With Gonioscopy Findings\nLiving with angle-related eye issues means adapting to a management plan that may include:\nDaily use of prescribed eye drops\nPeriodic monitoring with gonioscopy and IOP checks\nLifestyle changes to avoid triggers for angle-closure (e.g., dark environments, stress)\nUnderstanding the signs of a glaucoma flare-up (sudden pain, nausea, vision loss)\nPatient education and follow-up care are key to maintaining vision and quality of life.\nAdditional Common Questions\nIs gonioscopy painful?\nNo. Anesthetic eye drops are used, and the procedure is painless. You might feel mild pressure\nfrom the lens.\nHow long does it take?\nThe examination usually takes 5–10 minutes per eye.\nIs it done for both eyes?\nYes, both eyes are typically examined, even if only one shows symptoms.\nHow often should I have a gonioscopy?\nAs recommended by your eye doctor—commonly once a year or more often if you have\nglaucoma or narrow angles.\nAre there risks?\nGonioscopy is very safe. Rarely, mild irritation or redness may occur after the test.\nFAQs\n\n<!-- Page 716 -->\nQ: Can gonioscopy detect all types of glaucoma?\nA: Gonioscopy is specifically useful for angle-related glaucoma’s, such as open-angle and angle-\nclosure glaucoma. It complements other tests like OCT and visual field testing.\nQ: Who performs gonioscopy?\nA: It is performed by trained ophthalmologists or optometrists specializing in glaucoma and\nanterior segment evaluation.\nQ: Can it be done after eye surgery?\nA: Yes, though it may be deferred for a few weeks post-surgery to allow healing.\nQ: What happens if abnormal angles are found?\nA: Your doctor may recommend laser treatment (like iridotomy), medications, or surgery to\nmanage intraocular pressure and protect vision.\n"
