    "contentMd": "# Thyroid Eye Disease (Graves’ Eye Disease) – Complete Guide\n\nSource: `Eye Diseases & Conditions-compressed.pdf`, pages 777-781.\n\n_No embedded image was found for this section in the PDF._\n\n## Extracted text\n\n<!-- Page 777 -->\nThyroid Eye Disease (Graves’ Eye Disease) – Complete Guide\nOverview\nThyroid Eye Disease (TED), also referred to as Graves’ Eye Disease, is an autoimmune\ncondition where the body’s immune system mistakenly attacks tissues around the eyes. Most\ncommonly linked to Graves’ disease, an overactive thyroid disorder (hyperthyroidism), TED\ncan also occur in people with normal or underactive thyroid function. The inflammation and\ntissue buildup behind the eye can cause visible changes in appearance and impair vision, making\nearly detection and care essential.\nSymptoms and Causes\nCommon Symptoms\nSymptoms vary in severity and progression but may include:\nEye bulging (proptosis)\nSwelling around the eyes\nRedness and inflammation\nExcessive tearing or dry eyes\nLight sensitivity (photophobia)\nDouble vision (diplopia)\nEye pain or discomfort\nRestricted eye movement\n\n<!-- Page 778 -->\nEyelid retraction or puffiness\nCauses\nTED is primarily an autoimmune response. Factors that may trigger or worsen it include:\nAutoimmune Dysfunction: The immune system targets the tissues behind the eyes.\nThyroid Disorders: Especially Graves’ disease, but it may also occur in hypothyroid or\neuthyroid patients.\nGenetics: A family history of autoimmune diseases can increase risk.\nSmoking: A well-established risk factor; it also worsens symptoms.\nGender and Age: More common in women, especially between 30–60 years old.\nDiagnosis and Tests\nTo diagnose TED, a healthcare provider will review symptoms, perform an eye exam, and may\norder several tests:\nThyroid Function Tests: Blood tests for TSH, T3, and T4 hormone levels.\nEye Examination: Assessing eye movement, visual acuity, and bulging.\nOrbital Imaging: CT or MRI scans help detect muscle and fat tissue swelling behind the\neyes.\nExophthalmometry: Measures the degree of eye protrusion.\nUltrasound: May be used to assess soft tissue swelling and eye structure.\nManagement and Treatment\nThe approach to managing TED depends on the severity of symptoms and the phase of the\ndisease (active or inactive):\nNon-Surgical Treatments\nCorticosteroids: Reduce inflammation and swelling during the active phase.\nTeprotumumab: A newer, FDA-approved biologic specifically for TED.\nImmunosuppressive Therapies: Help control autoimmune responses.\nLubricating Eye Drops: For dryness and irritation.\nPrism Glasses: Help manage double vision.\nRadiation Therapy: Used in some cases to target orbital inflammation.\n\n<!-- Page 779 -->\nLifestyle Support\nStop smoking\nManage stress\nUse cool compresses\nElevate the head while sleeping\nTypes of Thyroid Eye Disease & Surgery\nTypes of TED\n1. Mild TED: Minor symptoms like dry eyes or slight puffiness.\n2. Moderate TED: Involves double vision, noticeable bulging, or eyelid retraction.\n3. Severe TED: May include vision loss, corneal exposure, or optic nerve compression.\nSurgical Options\nSurgery is typically reserved for patients whose symptoms persist after the active phase or\nimpact vision or appearance severely.\n1. Orbital Decompression Surgery: Removes bone or fat to reduce pressure behind the\neyes.\n2. Strabismus Surgery: Corrects misaligned eyes to relieve double vision.\n3. Eyelid Surgery: Repairs retracted or drooping eyelids to improve appearance and eye\nprotection.\nPrevention\nWhile TED cannot always be prevented, proactive measures can lower the risk or slow its\nprogression:\nQuit Smoking: Smoking greatly increases the risk and severity.\nControl Thyroid Function: Regular monitoring and treatment for thyroid disorders.\nProtect the Eyes: Use sunglasses and lubricating drops.\nRegular Screenings: Especially if you have Graves’ disease or a family history of\nthyroid issues.\nOutlook / Prognosis\n\n<!-- Page 780 -->\nThe prognosis for TED varies depending on the severity and how early it is treated:\nMild cases often resolve on their own or with minimal intervention.\nModerate to severe cases require medical or surgical treatment to prevent lasting\ndamage.\nVision-threatening TED is rare but requires urgent care.\nWith proper management, most people regain normal or near-normal function and appearance.\nLiving With Thyroid Eye Disease\nLiving with TED means adjusting to physical and emotional changes. Some tips for coping\ninclude:\nFollow-up Appointments: Consistent monitoring with an endocrinologist and\nophthalmologist.\nEmotional Support: Counseling or support groups can help manage anxiety or body\nimage concerns.\nPractical Adjustments: Use humidifiers, wear sunglasses, and practice good eye\nhygiene.\nHealthy Lifestyle: Balanced diet, stress management, and avoiding triggers.\nAdditional Common Questions\nCan I get TED if I don’t have Graves’ disease?\nYes. TED can occur in euthyroid (normal thyroid) or hypothyroid patients, although it is less\ncommon.\nHow long does TED last?\nTED typically has an active phase lasting 6–24 months, followed by an inactive phase where\ninflammation subsides.\nDoes TED recur?\nWhile TED usually follows a single course, flare-ups can happen, especially if thyroid function\nisn’t well-managed.\n\n<!-- Page 781 -->\nFAQs\nQ: Is Thyroid Eye Disease permanent?\nA: Not always. Some symptoms improve with treatment, while others like eye bulging may\nrequire surgery to correct.\nQ: Is TED contagious?\nA: No, it’s an autoimmune condition and not spread from person to person.\nQ: Can TED be treated naturally?\nA: While lifestyle changes help, medical treatment is often necessary, especially for moderate to\nsevere cases.\nQ: Who treats TED?\nA: Typically, a multidisciplinary team including an endocrinologist, ophthalmologist, and\nsometimes an oculoplastic surgeon.\nQ: Can TED cause blindness?\nA: In rare, severe cases, optic nerve compression can threaten vision. Early treatment minimizes\nthis risk.\n"
